  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is a serious criminal offense and is considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses, to make it appear as though the funds came from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is a federal crime under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Fines**: Up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n- **Imprisonment**: Up to 20 years in federal prison.\n\nAdditionally, money laundering charges often accompany other felony offenses, such as drug trafficking, fraud, or organized crime, which can lead to even harsher penalties.\n\nIf you are facing allegations of money laundering, it is crucial to seek legal representation from an experienced criminal defense attorney immediately.",
